no-unhandled-error

Disallow discarding expressions that are subtypes of Error. Enforces the
errore pattern where errors are returned as values and must be checked.

Source: custom rule, part of the errore convention (errore.org)

The Problem

When functions return Error | T unions (the errore pattern), callers must
check the result with instanceof Error before using it. If the return value
is discarded as a bare expression statement, the error is silently ignored.

  declare function getUser(id: string): Error | User;

  getUser("123");     // error: Error-typed return value is not handled

  await fetchData();  // error: Promise<Error | Data> resolved but not checked

What Gets Flagged

  - Call expressions whose return type includes Error (or any Error subclass)
    when the result is discarded as an expression statement
  - Awaited calls where the resolved type includes Error
  - Works with custom error subclasses (TypeError, NotFoundError, etc.)

What Is NOT Flagged

  - Assigning the result to a variable (you'll presumably check it)
  - void operator (explicit discard: void getUser("123"))
  - Functions returning void, undefined, or never
  - Non-call expressions (bare identifiers, property accesses)
  - Return statements (the caller handles it)
  - console.log, arr.push, and other void-returning methods

Correct Usage

  // Assign and check
  const user = getUser("123");
  if (user instanceof Error) return user;

  // Explicitly discard with void
  void getUser("123");

  // Use in return position
  function wrapper() { return getUser("123"); }

This rule pairs with the errore convention: return errors instead of throwing
them. Functions return Error | T, callers narrow with instanceof. If you
forget to check, this rule catches it at lint time.
